# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Line ending normalization
#
# This repo's .editorconfig declares end_of_line = crlf for all files
# (the [*] section sets it, and no extension-specific section overrides
# it). Without an explicit .gitattributes, git's behaviour depends on
# each developer's local core.autocrlf setting — Windows defaults to
# "true" (CRLF on checkout) while Linux/macOS default to "input" or
# "false" (LF on checkout). When a file is committed from a non-Windows
# machine it gets stored as LF in the git index, and the next CI run on
# Ubuntu sees LF on disk while the .editorconfig demands CRLF, which
# IDE0055 flags as a formatting error and fails the build.
#
# Pinning `text=auto eol=crlf` here makes the working tree always use
# CRLF on checkout regardless of OS or local git config, matching the
# .editorconfig convention. Existing files that were stored as LF need
# a one-time `git add --renormalize .` to be re-stored with CRLF.
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
* text=auto eol=crlf

# Explicit binary types — defense-in-depth alongside text=auto's
# content sniffing so git never tries to normalize line endings on
# them even if a heuristic misfires.
*.png  binary
*.jpg  binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif  binary
*.ico  binary
*.dll  binary
*.exe  binary
*.pdb  binary
*.snk  binary
